SplunkIt Performance Test Kit - Install Guide

NOTE: Please refer to the QUICKSTART file for summarized steps if you are
      already familiar with SplunkIt


NOTE: This is not a Splunk app (and does not follow typical app installations)


I. INTRO

  SplunkIt is a performance test kit to benchmark a single-indexer Splunk
  configuration in two different tests:

    a.  Index Test: adds a large static file to Splunk and measures indexing
        throughput.

    b.  Search Test: runs searches sequentially from SplunkWeb while
        streaming data into Splunk.

  The kit utilizes two separate test participants:

    a.  splunkit-server
        * Resides on the same machine as the Splunk instance under test
        * Generates all datasets
        * Makes changes to the Splunk instance
        * Controls splunkit-user

    b.  splunkit-user
        * Resides on a separate machine from the Splunk instance under test
        * Loads a browser and performs ad-hoc searches using SplunkWeb



II. SETUP

  (1) splunkit-server

    a.  How to Install:

        * Unzip splunkit-server.zip on the same machine as your Splunk
          instance, outside of the Splunk installation directory
        * Set SPLUNK_HOME and server_host in pyro.properties, as well as any
          other custom properties
        * See pyro.properties.default for all supported properties and their
          default values.

    b.  System Requirements:

        * Linux, MacOS, or Windows
        * Python 2.6+
        * TCP port 8000 opened for Splunk (default settings)
        * TCP ports 8080 and 8081 opened for splunkit-server (default)
        * Minimum 75GB free disk space on splunkit-server volume (default)
        * Minumum 75GB free disk space on Splunk installation volume (default)
        * Running Splunk 4.1 - 6.x.  May either be a fresh install or
          preexisting install.

  (2) splunkit-user

    a.  How to Install:

        * Unzip splunkit-user.zip on a remote machine
        * Set server_host in pyro.properties; this value must match
          the server_host value set in splunkit-server/pyro.properties

    b.  System Requirements:

        * Linux, MacOS, or Windows
        * Python 2.6+
        * Firefox 4 - Firefox 21 (must added to system path)
        * Some X server if using a headless machine, e.g. Xvfb
          (must be running)
        * Network connectivity to splunkit-server / Splunk machine



III. INDEX TEST

  (1) Install splunkit-server on the same machine as the Splunk instance
      (see SETUP above)

  (2) Generate the static 50GB data file

    a.  Navigate to the splunkit-server directory on the server machine

    b.  Run in terminal: "python bin/gendata.py"

        * this should take approximately 1 hour
        * If running the script over remote SSH, try nohup and & to keep the
          script alive; i.e. "nohup python bin/gendata.py &"

  (3) Index the generated data into index=splunkit_idxtest

    a.  Navigate to the splunkit-server directory on the server machine

    b.  Run in terminal: "python bin/indextest.py"

        * If running the script over remote SSH, try nohup and & to keep the
          script alive; i.e. "nohup python bin/indextest.py &"

    c.  Script should report indexing completion when finished

  (4) check kbps / EPS metrics in SplunkWeb:

    a.  Run search using SplunkWeb, if Index Test hasn't been run previously:

    index=_internal per_index_thruput series="splunkit_idxtest"
    | stats avg(kbps), avg(eps)

    -or-

    b.  Wait until step IV.(5) below for a more detailed view into indexing
    performance



IV. SEARCH TEST

  (1) Install splunkit-server and splunkit-user, if not done already
      (see SETUP above)

  (2) Start splunkit-user

    a.  Navigate to the splunkit-user directory on the user machine

    b.  Start Xvfb if needed; e.g. "nohup Xvfb :1 &" will run using display :1

    c.  Run in terminal (NOTE: set DISPLAY if/as needed):

        "python bin/searchtest.py"

        * If headless, precede script invocation with display variable;
          i.e. "export DISPLAY=:1; python bin/searchtest.py"

        * If running the script over remote SSH, try nohup and & to keep the
          script alive; i.e. "nohup python bin/searchtest.py &"

  (3) Start splunkit-server

    a.  Navigate to the splunkit-server directory on the server machine

    b.  Run in terminal: "python bin/searchtest.py"

        * If running the script over remote SSH, try nohup and & to keep the
          script alive; i.e. "nohup python bin/searchtest.py &"

  (4) Run Search Test

    a.  Search test will automatically begin when both the server and user
        have started

    b.  Test will run for 80 minutes (4800s) by default.

        * The first 4 minutes of the test are dedicated to preparing the test;
          searches will not be run during these 4 minutes.

  (5) Verify Results

    a.  From SplunkWeb, open dashboard 'SplunkIt Results - Summary' from the
        "Views" tab in the Search app to see a summary of results

    b.  From SplunkWeb, open dashboard 'SplunkIt Results - Indexing Details'
        from the "Views" tab in the Search app to see detailed indexing
        statistics

        * Shows stats for both the Index Test and Search Test

    c.  NOTE: Index Test statistics may be inaccurate or may include data from
        other test runs if both the following conditions are met:

        * the Search Test was run from a different splunkit-server directory
          than the one used to run the Index Test

        * the Index Test was run multiple times, or was run only partially, on
          the same running Splunk instance

  (6) Optional: Post your SplunkIt Results

    a.  Take a screenshot of your "SplunkIt Results - Summary" dashboard

    b.  Send the screenshot to splunkit@splunk.com, along with a description
        of your hardware configuration.

    c.  We'll post results at blogs.splunk.com/tag/performance to help other
        Splunk users with their deployments.

    d.  You can send feedback and questions to splunkit@splunk.com.



V. FAQ

  (1) How do I clean up the test environment if my test is interrupted?

    a. Interrupted while generating the 50GB static file:

        * Kill the server's gendata.py python script if it is still running
        * Re-run the server's gendata.py script

    b. Interrupted while indexing the 50GB file (Index Test):

        * Re-run the server's indextest.py script to restart indexing
          (see: III.(3))

    c. Interrupted while running the Search Test:

        * Kill the server's searchtest.py python script, if still running
        * Kill the user's searchtest.py python script, if still running
        * Kill the user's firefox process, if still running
        * Re-run the server's searchtest.py script normally (see: IV.(3))
        * Re-run the user's searchtest.py script normally (see: IV.(2))


  (2) What did SplunkIt do to my Splunk server?

    SplunkIt should be run on a clean Splunk instance, and after the test,
    this Splunk instance can be deleted.

    In other words, do not use a Splunk instance in-use to run SplunkIt if you
    expect it restored to its previous state.

    For reference however, here is the list of artifacts left by running
    SplunkIt by default:

    a.  Results Dashboards

        * $SPLUNK_HOME/etc/apps/search/local/data/ui/views/
          splunkit_results.xml

        * $SPLUNK_HOME/etc/apps/search/local/data/ui/views/
          splunkit_indexing_details.xml

        * Both of the dashboards remain enabled on the Splunk server

    b. Conf file changes

        * $SPLUNK_HOME/etc/apps/search/local/indexes.conf
          ** [splunkit_idxtest]
          ** [splunkit_searchtest]

        * $SPLUNK_HOME/etc/apps/search/local/viewstates.conf
          ** [*:gqwzm80t]
          ** [splunkit_results:_current]

        * $SPLUNK_HOME/etc/apps/search/local/inputs.conf
          ** monitor dir: splunkit-server/data/static
          ** monitor dir: splunkit-server/data/streaming
          ** monitor dir: splunkit-server/results

        * $SPLUNK_HOME/etc/apps/search/local/limits.conf
          ** [search] base_max_searches = 500

        * $SPLUNK_HOME/etc/users/admin/search/local/savedsearches.conf
          ** 84 scheduled saved searches, by default
          ** 18 saved searches for displaying results (results dashboards)

        * All of the above remain enabled on Splunk server, except for the
          scheduled searches, which are removed at the end of the Search Test



  (3) How do I extend SplunkIt to use custom searches?

    a.  Specify a custom 'usersearch' in pyro.properties in splunkit-server

    b.  Specify customs scheduled searches in scheduled_searches.txt

        * Format:
          <frequency in minutes>; <earliest time>; <latest time>; <search>

        * Alternative search entry format:
          <frequency in minutes>; <search>

        * Frequency must be in minutes and must be a factor of 60

        * Earliest and latest times can be any accepted Splunk time format,
          relative or absolute

        * Search string should appear exactly as it would in a Splunk search
          bar, with no preceding 'search' command


  (4) How do I extend SplunkIt to use a custom dataset?

    a.  Prepare a sample data file in the desired format with the following
        tokens in each event:

        * @TIME@: will be replaced by a timestamp

        * @FIELD@: will be replaced by custom fields

    b.  Set the 'datatype' field in pyro.properties to 'custom'

    c.  Specify custom dataset parameters in pyro.properties:

        * custom_sourcetype: custom sourcetype to apply to dataset, to allow
          custom timestamp/field extraction and line breaking with props.conf

        * custom_source_path: Path to your sample data file

        * custom_timestamp_format: format of timestamps to add to data,
          e.g. "%b %d %Y %H:%M:%S %Z"

        * custom_timestamp_token: token string to replace with timestamps

        * custom_field_token: token string to replace with custom fields

    d.  If necessary for timestamp/field extractiona and/or linebreaking, add
        a custom props.conf file to the Splunk instance

    e.  Finally, run the Index Test and Search Test normally


  (5) How do I change how much data to use in the index & search tests?

    a. Change the size of the static file to generate for the index test

        * Set static_filesize_gb to an integer of your choice;
          default is 50 (GB)

    b. Change the streaming data rate for the search test

        * Set streaming_datarate_gbph to an integer of your choice;
          default is 3 (GB per hour)


  (6) How do I set custom homepaths and coldpaths for the test data?

    a. Change where the static data is stored for the index test

        * Set custom_static_home_path in the server's pyro.properties file

        * Set custom_static_cold_path in the server's pyro.properties file

    b. Change where the streaming data is stored for the search test

        * Set custom_streaming_home_path in the server's pyro.properties file

        * Set custom_streaming_cold_path in the server's pyro.properties file


  (7) How do I disable/simplify parts of the test?

    a.  Disable scheduled searches in the search test

        * Set enable_scheduled_searches in the server's pyro.properties to
          False

    b.  Disable streaming data generation in the search test

        * Set enable_streaming_data in the server's pyro.properties to False


  (8) How do I extend SplunkIt to use more than one search user at once?

    a.  You can increase the number of search users in different ways:

        * Unzip splunkit-user.zip onto multiple systems or into different
          directories on the same system

        * Set agents_per_client parameter in the server's pyro.properties
          to greater than 1

        * Any combination of the above two options

    b. Set a new autostart condition:

        * In the server's pyro.properties, set client_count to the number of
          splunkit-user clients you want to use.

        * Search test will wait until (client_count * agents_per_client)
          threads have started

    c.  Run the Search Test normally.

        * All reported search times will be averages of all search user
          threads.


  (9) How do I make the search user run CLI tests only?

    a. Example properties files in both splunkit-server and splunkit-user
       are provided, as pyro.properties.cli, which you can use to
       overwrite pyro.properties.


  (10) Where do I look if I want to modify the test code?

    a.  All relevant code appears in the lib directory in both splunkit-server
        and splunkit-user:

        * kirsch.py - selenium code that interacts with SplunkWeb

        * pyro_test_classes.py - where the SplunkWeb and SplunkCLI Ad-Hoc search
          test cases are defined, using code from kirsch.py

        * pyro_server.py - code to help the server communicate with one or
          more clients and handle test results

        * pyro_client.py - code to help a client communicate with a server and
          initialize a particular test class

        * common.py - simple utility functions

    b.  Changes to the test code are unsupported


  (11) How do I extend SplunkIt to benchmark a distributed Splunk deployment?

    a.  SplunkIt currently only supports a single Splunk instance.  However,
        we hope to support distributed Splunk deployments in a future release
        using Universal Forwarders.



